38
00:01:51.520 --> 00:01:57.920
You'll be tasked to use a dataset of job postings to find trends in top data science jobs along with associated skills.

39
00:01:57.920 --> 00:01:57.920


40
00:01:57.920 --> 00:01:57.920


41
00:01:57.920 --> 00:02:02.800
Trends in the job market are a classic supply and demand problem.

42
00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:04.920
Looking at the axes of the graph, the

43
00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:12.320
"Quantity", or number of job postings, is the x-axis, and the "Price", or salary, is the y-axis.

44
00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:12.320


45
00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:12.320


46
00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:17.840
The yellow line, titled "Supply", is based upon the amount of those that are looking for employment.

47
00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:17.840


48
00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:17.840


49
00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:22.560
The red line, titled "Demand", is based upon the amount of employment opportunities.

50
00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:22.560


51
00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:22.560


52
00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:29.280
The point where supply and demand intersect, corresponds directly to salary or price.

53
00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:35.600
These lines are theoretical and in a real world scenario, supply and demand are more difficult to plot.

54
00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:38.240
However, the basics of this concept are still important to

55
00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:42.120
understand and are something we should look out for in this case study.

56
00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:42.680


57
